ðŸ”‘ What is Two Pointers?

You use two indices to traverse an array smartly, usually:
From both ends, or
One slow, one fast

Common pointer setups:
int left = 0;
int right = n - 1;

or

int slow = 0;
for (int fast = 0; fast < n; fast++) { ... }

ðŸ§  WHEN to use Two Pointers?
Use two pointers when: Array is sorted OR can be sorted

Problem asks for:
1)Pair / triplet
2)Closest sum
3)Remove duplicates
4)Partition array
5)Merge sorted arrays
6)Compare from ends

Keywords:

pair, sum, difference, closest, remove, sorte

IMPORTANT:-

ðŸ§  FINAL TWO-POINTER PATTERN MAP (MEMORISE THIS):-

ðŸ”¹ Pattern 1: Slow-Fast Pointers (In-place)
ðŸ‘‰ Modify array without extra space

ðŸ”¹ Pattern 2: Opposite-End Two Pointers
ðŸ‘‰ Sorted array, pair problems

ðŸ”¹ Pattern 3: Sorting + Two Pointers (K-Sum)
ðŸ‘‰ Pair â†’ Triplet â†’ Quadruplet

Key rules:-
1)Always sort
2)Skip duplicates
3)Fix one index, move two pointers

ðŸ”¹ Pattern 4: Partition / 3 Pointers
ðŸ‘‰ Divide array into regions

ðŸ”¹ Pattern 5: Merge from Back
ðŸ‘‰ Avoid overwriting

ðŸ”¹ Pattern 6: Greedy Two Pointers
ðŸ‘‰ Pair largest with smallest

ðŸ”¹ Pattern 7: Reverse Traversal Pointers
 Backspace String Compare

ðŸ”¹ Pattern 8: Advanced Pointer Logic
ðŸ‘‰ Precomputed boundaries


